Note = {16th International Conference on Computational Intelligence and
   Communication Networks, Indore, INDIA, DEC 22-23, 2024},
Organization = {Oriental University Indore; Institute of Electrical and Electronics
   Engineers Inc},
Abstract = {It takes a lot of work to gather a large amount of data to help in
   criminal investigation and prevention of crimes. The most effective
   methods for reporting crimes are insufficient for both civilians and law
   enforcement. The police and witness narrative summaries are frequently
   deemed to be too lengthy to read. Hence, there exists many research
   works that represents summary of those descriptive reports. But to make
   it easier, there should be certain phrases or words so that Police
   investigators can quickly understand criminal scenarios saving them from
   having to read the entire report. This can be accomplished with the use
   of criminal information extraction. Here, the proposed study uses a
   graph-based methodology and natural language processing techniques to
   extract crime-related keywords from in-depth police and witness
   narrative descriptions. Initially, the suggested work selected nouns,
   verbs, and adjectives from the crime reports and evaluated their
   importance scores. Based on the words' importance scores, a graph
   partitioning technique has been applied; following repeated runs of the
   algorithm, the words are classified into clusters. Each cluster in this
   instance, together with the words that reside within it, represent a
   different aspect of crime. These clustered words are considered as the
   keywords for representing the crime.},
