   Catania, ITALY, SEP 11-15, 2017},
Organization = {Univ Catania, Dept Math \& Comp Sci, Image Proc Lab; iCTLab; Micron;
   STMicroelectronics},
Abstract = {Object detection is the key module in most visual-based surveillance
   applications and security systems. In crime scene analysis, the images
   and videos play a significant role in providing visual documentation of
   a scene. It allows police officers to recreate a scene for later
   analysis by detecting objects related to a specific crime. However, due
   to the presence of a large volume of data, the task of detecting objects
   of interest is very tedious for law enforcement agencies. In this work,
   we present a Faster R-CNN (Region-based Convolutional Neural Network)
   based real-time system, which automatically detects objects which might
   be found in an indoor environment. To test the effectiveness of the
   proposed system, we applied it to a subset of ImageNet containing 12
   object classes and Karina dataset. We achieved an average accuracy of
   74.33\%, and the mean time taken to detect objects per image was 0.12
   sin Nvidia-TitanX GPU.},
